<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911226-0030</DOCNO><DOCID>911226-0030.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Saison Group:   Japanese Firm Is Prepared   To Buy SAS's ICH Stake</HL><DATE>12/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8</SO><CO>   K.SAI</CO><MS>CONGLOMERATES (CGL)CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)CONGLOMERATES (CGL)LODGING, CAMPGROUNDS (LOD)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>DENMARK (DA)EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)SCANDINAVIA (SCA)</RE><LP>   An executive of the Japanese conglomerate Saison Group,Tokyo, said the company is prepared to acquire the 40% stakeheld by Scandinavian Airlines System in Inter-ContinentalHotels Corp., the troubled luxury hotel chain already 60%owned by Saison. No price was given.   Japan's Kyodo news service said Saison's intention toassume 100% ownership in ICH, which operates about 100 hotelsaround the world, was made at a Tokyo news conference bySueaki Takaoka, representative of the Saison Group andchairman of the retail chain operator Seiyu Ltd. A spokesmanfor SAS wasn't reachable.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Takaoka said SAS is seeking a buyer because it islosing $100 million annually from its stake in ICH, mainlybecause of the hotel operator's debt, which exceeds $1billion. SAS had announced in September that it was lookingfor a buyer for its ICH stake.   Saison purchased ICH for $2.15 billion in 1988. SASacquired a 40% interest in ICH for $500 million in 1989 whenICH increased its capital.   If debt-servicing costs aren't considered, Mr. Takaokasaid, ICH is expected to produce pretax profit amounting toabout $70 million this year and about $100 million dollarsnext year.</TEXT></DOC>